FG-301 — Relief Palette on Page One (Decide Fast)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Put your two-line order text on the first page; make the brief prove it.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Page-one box: Primary (decide now, 1 line) + Fallback (limited remand block). Mirror the same text at the end.
	•	📝 Assignment: Paste a page-one relief box into your current draft.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Vacate & remand 21 days for findings (a–d). Alt: clarify footnote ‘not reached.’”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: The order should lead and close.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A small box labeled “Relief” at the very top margin.

⸻

FG-302 — Ten-Minute Record Audit (Pins • Quotes • Tabs)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: A quick audit avoids big credibility hits.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Timer 10: (1) One pin per paragraph, (2) quotes ≤25 words + page:line, (3) tab names match bookmarks. Log 5 fixes.
	•	📝 Assignment: Run the 10-minute audit; list five corrections.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Added 3 anchors, trimmed 2 quotes, fixed Tab 3 bookmark.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Momentum beats perfection.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A stopwatch beside three green check icons.

⸻

FG-303 — One-Page “Harmless Error” Rebuttal (Causation)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Answer harmless-error with causation and a small fix.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Map: Error (pin) → Effect (skipped factor/time) → Narrow remedy (findings in 21–30d). Keep it one page.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 6-line harmless-error rebuttal with two pins.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Wrong standard (Dkt 18:2) skipped harm (Tab 3 p.2) → likely different outcome → remand 21 days.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Show the “so what,” not adjectives.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Arrow chain: Error → Prejudice → 21-day Remand.

⸻

FG-304 — OA “Signal Log” (Who • Topic • Time • Ask)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Track hot topics live and aim your close at them.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Columns: Judge • Topic • Minutes • Quote/pin • Close hook. Use to pick the finishing ask.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 6-row signal log from your last OA recording.
	•	✅ Model Response: “J2—‘not reached’ (6m) → close: remand 21d for harm findings.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Signals choose your door.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A heat bar growing beside one issue.

⸻

FG-305 — Two-Sentence Status (What • Next)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Status letters move calendars when they are tiny.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Sentence 1—what happened with a pin; Sentence 2—next step + date. Attach draft order.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write a 2-sentence status for your live matter.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Order omits harm (Dkt 18:2). Set limited remand for findings within 21 days.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Short status = actionable status.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two lines connected to a small order strip.

⸻

FG-306 — Quote Table (≤25 Words • Page:Line • Purpose)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Organize quotes like evidence, not ornaments.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Table: Quote (≤25) • Page:line • Purpose (gap/standard) • Relief link. Place in appendix; cite once.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 6-row quote table for your best lines.
	•	✅ Model Response: “‘Did not reach harm’ — Dkt 18 at 2 — gap → remand.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Precision defeats paraphrase.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A quote ribbon aligned to a pin tile.

⸻

FG-307 — Exhibit Pairing (Auth First, Then Content)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Cite the auth page before the content page every time.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Ladder: Auth (902(11)/stamp/EXIF) → Content (invoice/screenshot) → Factor (harm/equities/public). Duplicate auth at tab front.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write two auth-first cites and insert into your brief.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Auth: Decl ¶4 (S-1 p.1) → Content: invoice (Tab 3 p.2) → Factor: harm (cost).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Provenance precedes persuasion.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A key icon before a page icon.

⸻

FG-308 — One-Page Appendix Guide (Legend • Crosswalk • Hash)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: A single page can cut reading time in half.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Legend (Dkt/Ex/Tab), Crosswalk (Issue → Tab p.#), Hash footer; put as Tab A.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a one-pager and export with hash line.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Legend: cites to PDF pages; Harm → Tab 3 p.2; SHA-256 41be22….”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Orientation = persuasion.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A front sheet with a fingerprint footer.

⸻

FG-309 — “Hold or Limited Remand” Micro-Ask
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Offer a small, dated door when the panel hesitates.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: One line: hold pending [X] or limited remand for [task] in [21–30d]; status on return.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft your micro-ask for today’s posture.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Hold 21d pending [case], or remand 21d for harm findings; status 7d after return.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Small asks move large calendars.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two tiny arrows to one calendar chip.

⸻

FG-310 — “Pin-First” Conclusion (Order Anchored to Pages)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: End with two pins + two-line order; nothing else.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Last paragraph: standard + two pins (Dkt/Tab) → order text (primary/fallback). No adjectives.
	•	📝 Assignment: Rewrite your conclusion to: pins → order.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Abuse; harm not reached (Dkt 18:2; Tab 3 p.2). Relief: remand 21d for findings; or clarify ‘not reached.’”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Conclusions are for signing, not summarizing.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two pin dots flowing into a small signature strip.
